<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Exporters Place Orders With Hungarian Distributors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1203170194 Taipei CNA in English 1246 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1203170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Gabor Kurti] </F>
  [Text] Budapest, March 11 (CNA) -- Orders worth US$50,000 
were placed by Hungarian distributors with 14 Taiwan exporters 
at a Thursday [10 March] meeting between the two sides, and as a 
result the Taiwan businesses can expect to see US$3 million of 
new business come their way, Sun Jui-lin, manager of the 
Budapest office of the China External Trade Relations 
Association, or CETRA, said. 
  Sun said that the Taiwan businessmen were impressed by their 
prospects in the Hungarian market, mainly because of the low 
rate of inflation here. But he admitted that the Hungarians 
were reticent to do more business because of their concerns 
about the relatively high cost of Taiwan products and the time 
it takes for them to be delivered, which can be up to three 
months. 
  He said that until the Taiwan companies feel assured of the 
reliability of doing business with the Hungarian importers 
through Hungarian banks, the time of delivery would be a 
sticking point between the two sides. 
  Another group of Taiwan business representatives will visit 
Hungary in June, Sun said. That delegation will include Taiwan 
importers as well as exporters, he stressed. In reciprocation, 
Hungarian manufacturers will have a chance to sell their wares 
in Taiwan when they participate in the Taipei International 
Trade Fair in October. 

</TEXT>

