<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   CETRA To Help Machinery Makers Tap Latin American Markets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1203091394 Taipei CNA in English 0717 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1203091394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 12 (CNA) -- The China External Trade 
Development Council (CETRA) will help local machinery 
manufacturers tap Latin American markets, a spokesman said 
Saturday [12 March]. 
  As part of the drive, the semi-official trade promotion body 
is organizing a delegation of machinery manufacturers and 
traders to attend an international trade fair to be held in 
Bogota, Colombia in July, the spokesman reported. 
  CETRA will provide transport subsidies for local machinery 
manufacturers who want to exhibit their products at the Bogota 
trade show, the spokesman said. 
  "We are also compiling a list of major Colombian machinery 
importers and will help local manufacturers negotiate trade 
deals with them," the spokesman said. "We hope we can sell all 
the Taiwan machines displayed at the Bogota show," he added. 
  The spokesman said the biennial Bogota Trade Fair used to 
focus on consumer goods, but, starting this year, it will also 
feature machines and other production equipment. 
  The demand for production facilities in Bogota and other 
Latin American countries has been growing steadily in recent 
years, fueled by recovering economies, the spokesman said. 
  Moreover, the spokesman said, Bogota has largely cut its 
tariff rates on machinery imports. "This is a good time for 
Taiwan machinery makers to penetrate that market," he noted. 
  CETRA will rent a large booth for local manufacturers to 
display their machinery at the Bogota fair, the spokesman said. 
"Local manufacturers of plastics, footwear, textile and molding 
machines are welcome to join the CETRA mission to tap the 
Colombian market," he added. 
  If the Bogota show turns out to be a success, the spokesman 
said, CETRA will use similar tactics to help local machinery 
manufacturers explore other Latin American markets. 

</TEXT>

