<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam Views Nuclear Issue During News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903125494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1240 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- Kim Yong-sam, 
president of the Republic of Korea (ROK), said here today his 
country shares the view with China that neither the north nor 
the south in the Korean peninsula should possess nuclear weapons. 
  At a press conference here this afternoon, Kim Yong-sam 
stressed that the ROK Government hopes that the North Korea 
nuclear issue could be settled through dialogue and peaceful 
means. 
  He said he also expressed this view at his meeting with 
Chinese President Jiang Zemin. 
  The ROK president also said that his current visit to China 
is of great significance for strengthening the substantial 
cooperation between the two countries. 
  Kim expressed his admiration for China's rapid economic 
growth, adding that in recent years the economic and trade 
cooperation and the exchange of experience between the two 
countries had benefited both sides. 
  He noted that the agreement on avoidance of double income 
taxation and prevention of tax evasion, signed between the two 
countries yesterday, would help promote Sino-ROK economic 
exchanges. 
  Kim said that during his visit, he had exchanged views with 
Jiang Zemin on expanding bilateral economic ties, and economic 
cooperation in the Asia and Pacific region. 
  The ROK president reaffirmed that his country would actively 
support China's re-entry to the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT). 

</TEXT>

