<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Senior Hong Kong Civil Servants </H4>
<F P=102> OW3103102094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1000 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3103102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 31 (XINHUA) -- A Chinese Foreign 
Ministry spokesman said here today that the Chinese side 
sincerely hopes that the civil servants working in various 
departments of the Hong Kong Government will rest assured and 
will continue to render service for the Government of the Hong 
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) and for the local 
people after 1997. 
  The spokesman made the remarks at a press confernece when 
asked to comment on a statement of the British side which 
proposes to discuss with the Chinese side a list of principal 
Hong Kong officials transcending 1997. 
  He said that there are clear stipulations in the 
Sino-British 
Joint Declaration and the Basic Law for the Hong Kong SAR, 
namely, candidates for the principal officials of the Government 
of the Hong Kong SAR shall be submitted to the central 
government for appointment upon normination by the SAR chief 
executive. 
  Therefore it is clear that the right to nominate and appoint 
the principal officials of the Hong Kong SAR Government rests 
with the SAR chief executive and the central government, 
respectively, rather than a case in which the candidates for the 
principal officials will be nominated by the British side and 
then submitted for consultation with the Chinese side, he said. 
  He reaffirmed that the Chinese side will act in strict 
accordance with the provisions stipulated in the Sino-British 
Joint Declaration and the Basic Law. 
  "The Chinese side sincerely hopes that the civil cervants 
working in the various departments of the Hong Kong Government 
will rest assured and perform their duties, and will continue to 
render service for the Hong Kong SAR Government and for the Hong 
Kong people after 1997," the spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

