<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Signs Law To Reduce Federal Employees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003222194 Beijing XINHUA in English 2158 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003222194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 30 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton signed a federal buyout bill into law today aimed 
at cutting federal government bureaucrats by 272,900 employees 
over five years. 
  Under the law, the federal government offers a lump sum of 
up 
to 25,000 U.S. dollars as a buyout to each of those who resign 
or retire provided he or she has completed 12 months of 
continuous service. 
  The U.S. President signed the legislation while vacationing 
in southern California. 
  The new law is part of the effort of the White House to slim 
the federal government which employs more than two million 
people. The law will help reduce the federal government 
workforce by 12 percent, bringing the figure below the 
two-million mark for the first time since 1966 and to the lowest 
level since 1950. 
  In a statement released by the White House, Clinton said 
that 
the law would help the government achieve goals of making 
government work better and cost less. 
  In a related development, White House Budget Director Leon 
Panetta announced that the Clinton administration had eliminated 
284 federal advisory committees, which are required by law, 
saving 17 million U.S. dollars a year. 
  Clinton had ordered a year ago that the 801 advisory 
committees that are not required by law be trimmed by a third to 
267. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

