<H3> <TI>   U.S. Fertilizer Executive Favors MFN Renewal for China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903121994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1136 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- The president of U.S. 
fertilizer giant Cargill said here today that the United States 
should extend the most-favored-nation trade status (MFN) toward 
China this June. 
  Speaking at a seminar on international trade of agricultural 
commodities, Cargill president Fritz Corrigan said China and the 
United States have close economic and trade relations. He 
expressed hope that Sino-U.S. economic relations would be 
maintained and strengthened. 
  He told XINHUA that during his meeting with U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor in Washington last February, he 
strongly advocated the renewal of China's MFN status. 
  Kantor was generally in favor of the extension of MFN 
status, 
Corrigan said. 
  He said that withdrawing China's MFN status would be 
unhelpful to Sino-U.S. cooperation and would definitely harm the 
economic and trade relations between the two countries. 
  According to John Crawshaw, president of Cargill 
Fertilizer's 
Southeast Asian branch, the U.S. fertilizer giant shipped the 
first batch of American wheat to China in 1972 when the then 
U.S. President Richard Nixon made his first China visit. 
  Cargill Fertilizer's business volume in China has topped 25 
million tons over the last two decades, including the purchasing 
and selling of over 20 varieties of agro-products. 
  Crawshaw said that Cargill has determined to invest more in 
China and would seek more partners. He anticipated that his 
company could complete the necessary procedures to be registered 
in China by the end of this year. 
  Cargill Fertilizer, with more than 70,000 employees 
worldwide, specializes in agro-business. The company's 
fertilizer sales volume worldwide exceeded seven million tons in 
1993. 
  Today's seminar was sponsored by China's Ministry of 
Agriculture, Cargill Fertilizer and the Potash and Phosphate 
Institute of Canada. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

