<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kazakh President Calls For New Eurasian Union </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903135794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1342 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 29 (XINHUA) -- Kazakh President 
Nursultan Nazarbayev has proposed setting up a "Eurasian Union," 
which he describes as an absolutely new grouping for members of 
the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). 
  "If this idea fails to gain broad support within the CIS, it 
could be formed by Russia and Kazakhstan," Nazarbayev stressed 
at a meeting in Moscow's State University today. 
  The union, in his opinion, should be based on principles 
different from those of the CIS, although he added that he was 
not calling for the restoration of the old Soviet Union or the 
formation of an empire. 
  Nazarbayev said that the new union should have 
supra-national 
bodies to coordinate the economic, defense and foreign policies 
of the member states with a council of heads of state and 
governments to discuss strategic matters. 
  "This should be followed by direct elections to a common 
parliament, which would coordinate the legislative activities of 
all the member states," Nazarbayev explained. 
  He added that a council for defense ministers should be 
formed to create an effective military bloc along with a foreign 
ministers' council to coordinate members' joint activities in 
the world arena. 
  He said the Eurasian Union should stipulate the introduction 
of a single document or citizenship for all members, compulsory 
concerted economic reform programs and the establishment of a 
supra-national currency. 
  However, Nazarbayev said that membership of the union should 
not interfere with any bilateral relations with third countries. 
  "The union should be based on the principle of equality, 
respect of sovereignty and independence of states, guaranteed 
rights of every man and woman and individuality of every state," 
he added. 
  Nazarbayev, who arrived in Moscow for his first three-day 
official visit to Russia, signed a "record number" of bilateral 
documents with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, including 
agreements on political, economic and military cooperation 
between the two former Soviet republics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

