<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii's Tax Plan Not `International Commitment' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802032094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0254 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802032094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 28 KYODO -- Japan's plan to extend a 
one- year tax reduction for fiscal 1994 is not an international 
commitment, a government source said Monday. 
  Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii told Treasury Secretary 
Lloyd 
Bentsen at their meeting near Frankfurt, Germany, that the 
planned income and residential tax cut is but a first step 
toward a more full-fledged tax reduction in the future. 
  The source said Fujii made the remarks "on an assumption 
that 
the ongoing debate over tax reforms will produce conclusion in 
one year." 
  "They're not an international pledge," the source said. 
  The government has been discussing a dramatic overhaul of 
the 
country's taxation system, with a more perpetual tax reduction 
on the agenda. The tax debate is scheduled to come up with some 
conclusions by the end of the year. 

</TEXT>

