<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Businesses Urged To Boost Imports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103121194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0103121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sozaburo Okamatsu, deputy minister of the Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry [MITI], held a news 
conference at the Japan Press Club in Uchisaiwai-cho, Tokyo, on 
the afternoon of 28 February. Touching on the Japan-U.S. 
economic friction at the news conference, Mr. Okamatsu said: 
"For Japan, the biggest issue is to achieve the economic growth 
driven by domestic demand." He also indicated that Japan needs 
to adopt a new macro policy to cut its current account surplus 
in addition to the four-point measure including deregulation 
under consideration by the government to open the Japanese 
market. 
  Referring to the automobile and auto parts sector on which 
both Japan and the United States have negotiated under the 
Japan-U.S. framework talks, the MITI deputy minister said: "The 
time has come for Japanese enterprises to make their own 
judgment to address trade imbalance between Japan and the United 
States." In this way, he urged the Japanese enterprises to work 
on their own to boost imports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

