<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `High Hopes' Pinned on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802073694 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 27 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2802073694 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "High Hopes Pinned on Visit by Defense </F>
Facilities Administration Agency Director General To the United 
States"] 
  [Text] Ichiro Yoneyama, director general of the Defense 
Facilities Administration Agency, an official charged with 
handling problems involving U.S. military bases in Japan, left 
Japan on 26 February for the United States to discuss with 
American officials the issue of streamlining and scaling down 
U.S. military bases on Okinawa. Mr. Yoneyama is due to meet 
with high-ranking U.S. Government officials in charge of 
overseas American military bases and leaders of the U.S. 
military. So far, working-level officials have visited 
Washington to discuss the issue with their American 
counterparts, but this is the first time that a top Japanese 
Government official in charge of handling the issue of 
streamlining and scaling down the U.S. military bases on Okinawa 
visits the United States to discuss the issue with American 
officials. 
  Everyone acknowledges that the key stumbling block impeding 
Okinawa's development is the existence of huge U.S. military 
bases on the island. Nobody can argue against the 
acknowledgement. The Okinawan people have thus far persistently 
pleaded for the streamlining and scaling down of the huge U.S. 
military bases on Okinawa. In response to this plea, however, 
the Japanese Government has not tried to work aggressively to 
resolve the issue. Although 22 years have passed since 
Okinawa's reversion to the Japanese rule, the return of Naha 
military port, which has been agreed upon between Japan and the 
United States, has yet to be materialized and the huge U.S. 
military bases still remain as they have been on Okinawa. 
  Upon Leaving Japan for Washington, Director General Yoneyama 
indicated that three issues -- the return of Naha military port 
and Yomitan auxiliary airfield and a halt to live-firing 
exercise by U.S. forces across National Highway No. 14 -- will 
be important objectives of his visit to the United States. Now 
that the director general specifically mentioned his intention 
to discuss those issues with American officials, we believe that 
he left Japan for Washington with a firm resolve. We hope that 
the visit by Director General Yoneyama to Washington will make a 
major headway in resolving the issue of streamlining and scaling 
down the U.S. military bases on Okinawa. 
  On 25 February when Director General Yoneyama held a news 
conference prior to his visit to the Untied States, a "liaison 
meeting on various problems at the U.S. facilities and their 
areas on Okinawa" (the liaison meeting attended by officials 
from the Okinawa Development Agency, the Foreign Ministry, and 
the Defense Facilities Administration Agency) was held. 
  During the meeting, Okinawa Development Agency Director 
General Uehara strongly asked that the liaison meeting not only 
exchange views on the three issues -- the return of Naha 
military port and Yomitan auxiliary airfield and halt to the 
live-firing exercises by U.S. forces across National Highway No. 
14 -- but discuss specific ways to resolve them. 
  The discussion of working-level officials alone cannot 
fundamentally resolve the issue of U.S. military bases on 
Okinawa. If government officials say they will "study," this 
means that they will do nothing. The discussion of working-level 
officials cannot resolve the issue fundamentally, but "they can 
only discuss how to build soundproof walls." The discussion of 
working-level officials will leave the issue of U.S. military 
bases on Okinawa unresolved forever. 
  Now that 50 years have passed since the end of World War II, 
the Japanese Government has perhaps begun to think seriously of 
ways to resolve the issue. Some are asserting that Japan should 
make international contributions while others are saying it is 
an economic power. They, however, cannot say so in a situation 
where more than 1 million of their compatriots have been 
hindered by huge foreign military bases to develop their economy 
and society and have suffered great inconvenience in their daily 
lives. 
  Fifty years have passed since the end of World War II. The 
time has come to resolve fundamentally the issue of U.S. 
military bases on Okinawa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

