<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Hold Security Talks With PRC, Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802115094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Feb 
94 Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2802115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Security dialogue between Japan and China, as well 
as Japan and Russia, will successively start among defense 
officials. Senior officials from the Defense Agency [DA] and the 
Chinese Ministry of National Defense [CMND] will hold talks in 
Beijing on 1 March. Officials of the Russian Ministry of 
Defense [MD] will visit Japan on 28 March for exchanges on 
defense studies with Japanese officials. Because Japan and 
China have not held regular security consultations before, they 
intend to take the opportunity to build a regular and continuous 
framework for exchange of views. 
  Among those who will attend the Japan-China security talks 
are: Ken Sato, DA's defense councilor; Toshimasa Fujiwara, chief 
of the fifth section of the DA Joint Staff Council; and senior 
CMND officials. They will exchange views on the whole situation 
in the Asia-Pacific region, including the DPRK's (North Korea's) 
suspected nuclear development. The prevailing view within the 
DA is that "China will become the largest unstable factor in the 
Asian region from a medium-to-long perspective," (as stated by a 
senior DA official). At the time of the upcoming talks, the DA 
intends to establish a stage for dialogue with Chinese military 
authorities to promote mutual understanding. 
  Defense study exchanges between Japan and Russia are hosted 
alternately by DA's National Institute for Defense Studies and 
the Military Strategic Center under the Russian General Staff 
Office. The upcoming exchanges will be the third case and will 
also be the first since February last year. Russian officials 
who will visit Japan include: Lukyanov, acting chief of the 
International Treaty Directorate of the General Staff Office, 
and Zolotorev, chief of MD's Information Analysis Center. 

</TEXT>

