<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nakasone Views Possible LDP-Shinseito Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702222894 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2702222894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with former Japanese Prime Minister </F>
Yasuhiro Nakasone by correspondent Hiroyuki Miyano in London on 
24 February] 
  [Text] London, 24 Feb -- Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro 
Nakasone granted an interview to SANKEI SHIMBUN at a London 
hotel on the morning of 24 February. During the interview, he 
noted that the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] should respond 
flexibly to the future political realignment while considering 
forming an alliance with Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] so that 
the party will be able to open the way to recapturing power. 
  Concerning a possible alliance and cooperation between the 
LDP and Shinseito, Nakasone said: "When forming an alliance 
with other parties in the political realignment, the LDP should 
first take into account (the similarity of) basic policies. It 
should allow minor policy differences and join with forces based 
on a general similarity. It should be agreed between alliances 
that any possible obstacles to forging mutual agreements will be 
eliminated." In this way, he noted that the LDP should decide 
whether to form an alliance with Shinseito based on a similarity 
of policies and that the decision should not be affected by 
emotional discord. 
  He also said: "The LDP should deal with the Hosokawa 
government with the principle of being fair and just. It cannot 
take power unless it approaches the government as close as 
possible. Just like in sumo wrestling, the LDP will grab the 
government by the arm and push it out." 
  His remark indicates that at this stage, the LDP needs to 
consider not only forming an alliance with Shinseito but also 
maintaining a position equidistant between Shinseito and other 
forces, such as Sakigake [Harbinger], which have had 
confrontations with Shinseito and Komeito [Clean Government 
Party]. By doing so, it will be able to form an LDP-led 
coalition government, Nakasone suggested. 
  Commenting on similar remarks made by former Foreign 
Minister 
Michio Watanabe on the alliance with Shinseito, Nakasone said, 
"Mr. Watanabe has acted based on the same idea as mine," thus 
giving support to Watanabe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-4692 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas040__a94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-040-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa's Proposal for Coalition Merger Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702223894 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2702223894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi </F>
Takemura by unidentified reporter; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Would you describe your opinion 
on prospects for a realignment of political parties? 
  [Takemura] Political circles are being urged to catch up 
with 
the new election system, and a realignment of political parties 
is becoming a realistic and vivid topic. In the next general 
election, we must not simply seek the majority power or 
quorum-oriented alliances. I think that in the next election we 
should take the first step based on our own judgment of Japan's 
future and the direction of its politics. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] In a recent speech, you noted that a 
regrouping of parties should be carried on in view of three 
factors: the perception of the times, political ideals, and 
political style. Could you explain these a little? 
  [Takemura] Each party must have a clear political ideal or 
basic policy. I think that an interparty alliance should be 
discussed according to how distant a party is from others in 
such official positions. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] What do you mean exactly by the 
perception 
of the times? 
  [Takemura] Unlike the period of rightist-leftist antagonism 
under the cold war structure, we now can afford to choose 
political partners from a wide range, from the Liberal 
Democratic Party [LDP] to the Social Democratic Party of Japan. 
This is the time in which we have to find appropriate partners 
to hammer out new goals. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Could you define the political ideal? 
  [Takemura] Basically, it is a party's stands toward the 
Constitution, the direction of the nation, and the 
implementation of democracy. Individual subjects include 
education, welfare, and the environment. Of course, security 
policy is also an important subject. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Then, what is your description of 
political style? 
  [Takemura] The public is strictly observing in what manner 
parties collect and spend money, and in what manner they manage 
their own personnel and organization. So, I think a policy is 
not enough for a party to win the public's confidence. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Do you say this to clarify a gap between 
your party and the Shinseito-Komeito [Japan Renewal Party-Clean 
Government Party] team? 
  [Takemura] I do not want to believe that the two parties 
have 
clear problems in their styles; however, some specific persons 
may have such problems. Probably, one of the most important 
points is (in what manner) the parties makes decisions (on their 
courses of action). 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] What is your stand toward the "ordinary 
nation" proposal made by Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro 
Ozawa? 
  [Takemura] Mr. Ozawa described that idea in various ways, 
but, generally speaking, the proposal for being an ordinary 
nation is being discussed in connection with Japan's military 
role in the world. I guess that advanced Western nations look 
normal to him, and he wants to make Japan play a military role 
equal to that of their levels. But it is impossible for Japan 
to achieve that objective without a revision of the 
Constitution. I think that the public takes a negative stand 
toward such an idea because the Japanese people still continue 
their regret over their nation's behavior during the war. The 
most urgent question for the international community is how 
human beings can jointly solve contradictions in various 
nonmilitary fields. As a matter of fact, coping with regional 
conflicts is a very important subject, but global environmental 
problems are even more critical. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] What is your comment on Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa's proposal for a unification of the 
parliamentary groups of all the coalition parties? 
  [Takemura] It is hard for me to see whether this is needed 
for managing the current Diet session or for a party realignment 
in preparation for the next general election. I cannot go for a 
drastic idea like that. Because each coalition party has its 
unique standpoint, it is too reckless to merge all of them into 
one parliamentary group or party all at once. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Do you think that the prime minister's 
proposal affects your plan for a merger of Sakigake [Harbinger] 
and the Japan New Party [JNP]? 
  [Takemura] I am seriously worried about that. We have been 
dealing with each other with much respect concerning an 
engagement to the JNP. I would like to have a serious talk with 
Mr. Hosokawa as soon as possible. This issue affects the very 
foundation of my party. I feel that the proposal ruins our 
steady steps up to now. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] There is an opinion that the next general 
election should be fought between the LDP and the anti-LDP 
group. What is your comment on that? 
  [Takemura] I am skeptical over an election under such an 
artificial bipolar framework. It is theoretically possible to 
form a new party only for one's survival in the next election, 
but we would lose the public's confidence if we dissolve the 
party immediately after the election. Two-party politics is not 
a necessary condition for a single-seat constituency system. In 
particular, Japanese politics is undergoing a transitional 
period. For the time being, sound development would be ensured 
under the multiparty system, rather than under the two-party 
system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

